## Anti-patterns — DO NOT DO THIS

The summary critic will reject these; reject them yourself before invoking the critic.
Each one is a way of making the rule "pass" without addressing the root cause:

- **`NONDET` on a side-effect-bearing call.** `NONDET` summarizes a call as a **no-op
  body** returning a non-deterministic value. Applied to `transfer`, `transferFrom`,
  `mint`, `burn`, `swap`, `wrap`, `unwrap`, `deposit`, `withdraw`, `accountFor*`,
  `update*`, or any function whose semantics IS the side effect, every such call becomes
  a silent zero-effect call — catastrophically unsound. `NONDET` is appropriate ONLY for
  pure / view-shaped functions whose return value is the only thing the protocol depends
  on, AND where you have no constraint to express on that return value.

- **Wildcard scope on contract-specific calls.** `function _.foo(...)` matches *every*
  contract's `foo`. If the diagnosis names a specific callee
  (e.g. `TradeBridge.settleFees()`), target that contract by name, not the global
  wildcard. Casting a too-wide net poisons unrelated proofs.

- **`persistent` ghosts used as HAVOC armor.** `persistent` is for state that genuinely
  outlives every external call (a global supply counter, a monotone clock). Marking a
  ghost `persistent` so it survives a specific unresolved call's HAVOC hides the call's
  effect from verification rather than modeling it. The right fix is to resolve the call
  (Strategy B), not to dress the ghost in armor.

- **Mirror ghosts that shadow contract storage.** Don't model `balanceOf` / `totalSupply`
  / `paused` / etc. with a ghost that hooks every storage write to keep a parallel copy. CVL has
  direct storage access; use it. Ghosts are for state outside the verification scope or
  for derived values that aren't materialized in storage.

- **Removing the assertion.** "The rule passes if I delete the assert" — yes, and now the
  rule proves nothing.

- **Adding unrelated `require`s on rule preconditions to dodge the failing path.** If the
  only way the rule passes is to constrain inputs so the buggy execution is unreachable,
  the rule has stopped testing its property. The exception is when the constraint is a
  real protocol invariant — in that case formulate it as such (Strategy A) and
  `requireInvariant`, do not bury it as an opaque `require`.

- **Bare `require` without justification.** A `require` whose truth you can't justify —
  by an invariant, a justification rule, or an explicit citation of the system document —
  is spec weakening with extra steps. Either prove it or call it out explicitly in your
  rationale as an unproven assumption.

- **Solidity stubs without a paired validation rule.** If you propose a stub via the
  `addendum` field (Strategy B.b), you MUST pair it with a CVL rule that validates the
  eventual real implementation matches the stub's behavior. A stub on its own describes
  behavior the actual implementation may not deliver; the validation rule is what makes the
  stub-as-scaffolding safe. (Remember, the validation rule does NOT belong in the
  delivered `proposed_cvl` but in `addendum`.)

- **Contradicting the system document.** A summary or invariant that's locally
  well-formed CVL but inconsistent with the design described in the system document is
  wrong. If your remediation contradicts the system doc, re-examine — the diagnosis or
  your reading of it is probably off.
